{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Even if the algorithms used in decisionmaking processes are unbiased, the data they are trained on may contain historical biases, leading to discriminatory outcomes [62].",
    "Calmon et al.",
    "stated that the presence of historical discrimination in linear datasets, such as the widely studied Adult Income dataset used for evaluating fairness in machine learning, can result in biased predictions despite high model performance when using such biased data for training [97,124].",
    "For example, suppose a training dataset for an employee hiring algorithm only includes data from past hires, and past hiring practices were biased against certain groups.",
    "In that case, the algorithm will continue perpetuating that bias in hiring decisions."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Even if the algorithms used in decisionmaking processes are unbiased, the data they are trained on may contain historical biases, leading to discriminatory outcomes [62].",
